NER (Named-entity recognition)

A subtask of IE (information extraction) that identifies and classifies named entities mentioned in unstructured text into pre-defined categories such as person names, organizations, locations, time, quantities, monetary values, etc.

Use Cases of Named Entity Recognition

  • Classifying Content: For example, automating online content for articles by tagging the major people, organizations, and places discussed. This enables automated categorization of articles in defined hierarchies to help with content discovery
  • Efficient Search Algorithms: For online publisher, NER be run once on all documents and the relevant entities (tags) associated with each are stored separately. This could speed up the search process as a search term will be matched with the smaller list of entities for each article.
  • Content Recommendations: In online publishing, NER can be used to recommend similar articles by extracting entities from a particular document and recommending the others that have the most similar entities mentioned.
  • Customer Support: NER can be used for handling the online customer support by scanning through the mentions in your customers feedback. With NER named entities including location and product can be pulled out, then then used to categorize the complaint and assign it to the relevant department for handling.

spacyr

provides an R wrapper around the Python spaCy package. It offers easy access to the following functionality of spaCy:

  • parsing texts into tokens or sentences
  • lemmatizing tokens
  • parsing dependencies (to identify the grammatical structure of the sentence)
  • identifying, extracting, or consolidating token sequences that form named entities or noun phrases

It also allows a user to request additional token-level attributes directly from spaCy. spacyr also takes care of the installation of not only spaCy but also Python itself, in a self-contained miniconda or virtualenv environment, and can install additional language models or upgrade spaCy as new models and versions become available.

library("spacyr")
spacy_initialize(model = "en_core_web_sm")

Read and transform data

# read as a tibble
df = read.csv('./data/news_headlines.csv', stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# remove duplicates
df = df[!duplicated(df$headline),]

# Transformations
df$publish_date = as.Date(df$publish_date, "%m/%d/%y")

df$publish_year = lubridate::year(df$publish_date)
df$publish_mon = lubridate::month(df$publish_date, label = TRUE, abbr = TRUE)

df = df %>%
  mutate(headline_len = str_count(headline))

df = df %>%
  filter(headline_len >= 6)  # remove short headlines

df %>%
  filter(headline_len >= 10)  %>% # headline length > 10 chars
  select(-publish_year, -publish_mon, -headline_len) %>%

Topic Modeling

Topic modeling is an unsupervised, technique for classification of text data into natural groups or topics. With topic modeling, large sets of documents (eg: blogs, news articles, etc.) are scanned in order to detect word or phrase patterns and to automatically cluster them into word groups that best characterizes the set of documents. It is unsupervised in that the text data is unlabeled and there is no training. Generally, the criteria for classification is unknown in advance. Topic modelling helps with the following:

  • Discovery of hidden topical patterns present across the collection of documents
  • Annotating documents according to these topics
  • Using these annotations to organize, search and summarize texts

In business, topic modeling can be used for - discovering hidden topics in customer feedback to help organizations focus the most severe customer issues - summarizing text in journals to enable users to recall content more efficiently. - building a recommendation system. There are many techniques that are used to obtain topic models, namely: Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA), Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA), Correlated Topic Models (CTM), and TextRank.

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA)

Is an unsupervised classification method designed for text data. Rather than relying on labeled (eg: hand-coded data sets), it is a probabilistic topic model that uses statistical algorithms to analyze words in raw text documents, to uncover thematic structure of the both the corpus and individual documents. To use it requires: - A document-term matrix - The number of topics you would like the algorithm to pick up.

LDA treats each document as a mixture of topics, and each topic as a mixture of words. This allows documents to overlap each other in terms of content, rather than being separated into discrete groups. Only the documents and words can be observed, not the topics whose structure is hidden (eg: latent). Hence LDA seeks to infer topic structure given known words and documents.
For example, given the following set of documents in a corpus:

  • Doc 1: I ate a peanut butter sandwich for breakfast.
  • Doc 2: I like to eat almonds, peanuts and walnuts.
  • Doc 3: My neighbor got a little dog yesterday.
  • Doc 4: Cats and dogs are mortal enemies.
  • Doc 5: You must not feed peanuts to your dog.

The LDA model discovers the different topics that the documents represent and how much of each topic is present in a document. For the above, LDA may produce the following results:

Topic 1: 30% peanuts, 15% almonds, 10% breakfast, which can be interpreted as a food topic.
Topic 2: 20% dogs, 10% cats, 5% peanuts, which can be interpreted as a topic dealing with pets/animals.

  • Doc 1 and Doc 2: 100% Topic 1
  • Doc 3 and Doc 4: 100% Topic 2
  • Doc 5: 70% Topic 1, 30% Topic 2

library(topicmodels)
library(textstem)

# sample smaller set of docs
set.seed(1234)
cdf = df %>%
  filter(publish_year == 2019)  %>%
  sample_n(1000) 


hlCorpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(cdf$headline))

hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, removePunctuation)  # remove punctuation
hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, removeNumbers)      # remove numbers
hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, stripWhitespace)    # remove white space

# stop and custom stop 
hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, removeWords, c(stopwords('english')))

hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, lemmatize_strings) # lemmatizaton
#hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, stemDocument)  #stem words using SnowBall stemmer


hlCorpus <- tm_map(hlCorpus, removeWords, c( 'says', 'will', 'can',  
                'talk', 'tell', 'begin', 'one', 'two', 'first', 'say', 'take', 'get',
                'may', 'not', 'new', 'make', 'back', 'see', 'use',  'australia',
                'australian', 'change'))

dtm <- dtm[sel_idx, ]

In this case, there were no rows which contained all 0s hence there was no change in the number of terms

find the best k

Recall that LDA requires that we supply the number of topics (K). If you have prior knowledge on the topic structure, this can be used to inform your selection of a reasonable value for K. Too few could result in groupings of unrelated content while too large could risk being overly granular with the topic categories. There are several statistical measures that can help in finding an optimal value for K.
Perplexity is one and is used to measure how well a probability model predicts a sample. As applied to LDA, for a given value of K, one can estimate the LDA model by comparing perplexity across different models with varying ks. The model with the lowest perplexity is generally considered the best.

Ive chosen to look at models with K up to 11 topics. The min number is always 2 and you will need to experiment to determine the top threshold. Heres Ive chosen 11 ffor a total of 10 models to review.

#mod_log_lik = numeric(0)
mod_perplexity = numeric(0)
topics <- c(2:11)  

for (i in topics){
  mod <- LDA(dtm, k = i, method = "Gibbs", 
             control = list(seed=1234) ) # random seed for consitent results between runs
  #mod_log_lik[i] = logLik(mod)
  mod_perplexity[i] = perplexity(mod, dtm)
}
mod_perplexity <- mod_perplexity[!is.na (mod_perplexity)] # remove NA at first position

# plot
plot(x=topics, y=mod_perplexity, type = "b", xlab = "Number of topics", ylab = "Perplexity")

Looks like k of 11 is the best given the lowest perplexity

per-term-per-topic matrix

hl_lda <- LDA(dtm, k = 11, control = list(seed = 1234))
hl_lda
## A LDA_VEM topic model with 11 topics.
# beta (per-term-per-topic) 
hl_topics <- tidy(hl_lda, matrix = "beta")
hl_topics %>%
  arrange(term, -beta)  %>%
  head()
## # A tibble: 6 x 3
##   topic term       beta
##   <int> <chr>     <dbl>
## 1     1 aaco  1.91e-  3
## 2     9 aaco  6.36e- 29
## 3     8 aaco  4.51e-319
## 4     3 aaco  6.58e-320
## 5     7 aaco  6.47e-320
## 6     6 aaco  3.29e-320

Observe that words can be associated with more than one topic. For each combination, the model computes the probability (beta) of that term being generated from that topic. Here we see that aaco is more likely to be assigned to topic 1

per-document-per-topic

tidy(hl_lda, matrix = "gamma")  %>%
  arrange(document, -gamma)  %>%
  head()
## # A tibble: 6 x 3

## 3 1            2 0.00824
## 4 1           10 0.00824
## 5 1            1 0.00824
## 6 1            3 0.00824

Just as words can be associated with more than one topic, documents can be associated with more than one topic. Here we see that document 1 is more likely to be assigned to topic 7.

Show the 10 terms that are most common within each topic.

hl_top_terms <- hl_topics %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  top_n(10, beta) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -beta)

hl_top_terms %>%
  mutate(term = reorder_within(term, beta, topic)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(beta, term, fill = factor(topic))) +
    geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
    facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free", ncol=2) +
    theme_classic(base_size = 16) + 
    scale_y_reordered()

Having domain knowledge would allow one to better assess whether or not the topics makes sense, that is being familiar with the news headline in Australia for 2019. It is also possible that the model did not do a good job in categorizing the topics as some words do not appear related so more granularity may be in order, such as increasing the number of topics.
